The start symbol S has only two binary rules:  
1. S → NT4 NT77  
2. S → NT13 NT69  

Examine each possibility against the given 17-token string  

t54 t11 t7 t34 t78 t9 t11 t3 t62 t48 t17 t0 t47 t18 t3 t11 t78  

--------------------------------------------------------------------
1.  S → NT4 NT77  
• NT4 is lexical and can generate only t54 or t65.  
  – To match the first word t54, NT4 must produce exactly that single token.  
• Therefore NT77 must generate the remaining 16 tokens (positions 2–17).  

NT77’s binary rule is NT77 → NT51 NT78 (its only rule that yields more than one token; the alternatives ‘t47’ and ‘t34’ would give just one token).  
Hence the first word of the 16-token suffix must come from NT51.

NT51 → NT34 NT69  
Thus the very first token of the suffix is produced by NT34.

But NT34 can produce only  
 a) the single terminal t78,  
 b) the single terminal t9, or  
 c) a two-symbol string beginning with whatever NT61 produces (NT34 → NT61 NT47, NT47 → t84).  
NT61, in turn, can yield t62, t17, t40…, but never t11.

Consequently NT34 can never start with t11, yet the first token of the suffix is t11.  
So S → NT4 NT77 cannot generate the string.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
2.  S → NT13 NT69  
NT69 has exactly one rule: NT69 → NT23 NT6, with  
 NT6 → t18  
 NT23 → NT73 NT41, and both NT73, NT41 → t9  

Hence any string produced by NT69 must end with “… t9 t9 t18”.  
Our target string ends with “… t3 t11 t78”, and nowhere in it do two consecutive t9’s occur.  
Therefore the string cannot be derived via S → NT13 NT69.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
Both possibilities for S fail, so the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

The start symbol S has only two possible first-level derivations:

1. S → NT4 NT77  
2. S → NT13 NT69

Case 1: S → NT4 NT77  
NT4 can generate ‘t54’, matching the first word of the string.  
NT77 must then cover the remaining 20 tokens.  
The only way for NT77 to expand to more than one token is NT77 → NT51 NT78.  
Whichever way NT51 is expanded, NT78 must generate the final part of the string.

The options for NT78 are  
• NT78 → ‘t72’ (one token)  
• NT78 → ‘t33’ (one token)  
• NT78 → NT5 NT16 (ends with NT16 → ‘t28’, so the very last token would have to be ‘t28’).

Our string ends with ‘t7’, not ‘t28’, and it contains extra tokens after its single ‘t72’.  
Therefore no expansion of NT78 can match the tail of the given string, so Case 1 fails.

Case 2: S → NT13 NT69  
NT69’s only form is NT69 → NT23 NT6 with NT6 → ‘t18’.  
Hence any sentence derived via this branch must end with ‘t18’, but the given string ends with ‘t7’.  
Thus Case 2 is impossible.

Since neither of the two possible top-level derivations can yield the given 21-token string, the grammar does not generate it.

No

Because the only possible start-rules are  

1. S → NT13 NT69  
2. S → NT4 NT77  

and  

• NT69 must eventually produce token t18 (via its compulsory NT6 → 't18'), yet t18 never appears in the given string, so rule 1 cannot yield the string.  

• NT4 can generate only the single terminals t54 or t65.  In rule 2, NT4 would have to cover the very first symbol of the string, but the first symbol is t62, not t54 or t65, so rule 2 also cannot match.

Since neither of the two start productions can generate the provided token sequence, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only way the terminal t3 can be produced in this grammar is through the rule  
  NT1 → 't3'.  

NT1 itself appears in exactly one binary production:  
  NT66 → NT13 NT1  

Because NT1 is the right-hand child in that rule, every derivation that contains the terminal t3 will necessarily produce all the tokens generated by NT13 first, and the token t3 will appear only after them.  
In other words, in any sentence generated by the grammar, t3 can never be the very first token.

The string we are asked to check, however, begins with t3.  
Since the grammar cannot place t3 at the start of any derived string, the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT13 NT69  
2. S → NT4 NT77  

In Chomsky normal form every non-terminal either produces exactly one terminal symbol or two non-terminals, and there are no ε-productions listed in the grammar.

If S → NT4 NT77 were used, the very first token produced must come from NT4.  
NT4 has only terminal rules  
 NT4 → 't54' or NT4 → 't65'  
so the derived string would necessarily begin with t54 or t65 – not with t72.  
Hence this production cannot generate the given string.

Therefore S must derive via S → NT13 NT69, so the first token must come from NT13.  
NT13 has only the following alternatives:

NT13 → NT70 NT46  
NT13 → NT32 NT21  

Examining the leftmost symbols each of these can yield:

• NT70 → NT76 NT7 (first token t79)  
    or NT70 → NT60 NT13 (first token t47 or t29 from NT60)  
• NT32 → 't11' or 't24'

Thus the first token produced by NT13 can only be t79, t47, t29, t11 or t24 – never t72.

Since the target string begins with t72 and no derivation from S can start with that token, the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

The only non-terminal that can produce the terminal ‘t28’ is  

 NT16 → 't28'.

NT16 appears in exactly one rule of the grammar:

 NT78 → NT5 NT16     (so NT78 always yields a two-token suffix: one token from NT5 followed by ‘t28’).

NT78 itself occurs only in

 NT77 → NT51 NT78.

Therefore every derivation that ends with ‘t28’ must pass through

 S → NT4 NT77 → NT4 NT51 NT78 → NT4 NT51 ( NT5  NT16 ).

Consequently:
• the first token must be generated by NT4 (NT4 → 't54'),  
• the last token (token 35) is ‘t28’, produced by NT16, and  
• token 34 (the one immediately before ‘t28’) must be produced by NT5.

But NT5 can produce only the single terminal ‘t39’ or a two-token sequence

 NT38 NT74    (t47 t47 or t29 t47)  
 NT83 NT9      (t7 followed by something)  
 NT26 NT58    (t42 followed by something).

Hence NT5 can never yield the single terminal ‘t43’, yet token 34 in the string is ‘t43’.  
This contradiction shows that no derivation can generate the required ending “… t43 t28”.

Since the only possible derivation of ‘t28’ fails, the given string cannot be produced by the grammar.

No
